- VSCode Version: 1.10.2 + 1.11.0-insider
- OS Version: OSX 10.11.6 

Steps to Reproduce:

I have a node app which makes heavy use of Bluebird Promises and Generators.  Breakpoints are very unreliable within the Promises.

For example, in the below code, a breakpoint set on `Promise.coroutine...` will break on `return new Promise`, or in the method below this one (which also returns a Promise).

    import 'babel-polyfill';
    import { Promise } from 'bluebird';
    import { CreditCard, ECard } from '../models';
    import request from 'request';
    import moment from 'moment';

    function generateVirtualCard(amount, startDate, endDate, creditCardId, ecardId) {
        return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
            Promise.coroutine(function *() {
                const creditCard = yield CreditCard.findOne({ where: { creditCardId: creditCardId } });
                if (creditCard !== null) {
                    const virtualCard = yield createVirtualCard(amount, startDate, endDate, creditCard, ecardId);
                    resolve(virtualCard);
                } else {
                    reject({ error: 'generate virtual card error' });
                }
            })()
            .catch(error => { reject({ error: error }); });
        });
    }

- VSCode Version: Insider
- OS Version: macOS

Steps to Reproduce:

1. use this program:
   ```js
   console.log(1); console.log(1); console.log(1); console.log(1); console.log(1); console.log(1);
   ```
2. set column breakpoints just before the 'c' of the inner 4 console.logs:
   ![2017-03-30_12-15-18](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1898161/24499613/94de502e-1542-11e7-9703-69b7e6a7f5d4.png)
   ![2017-03-30_12-16-36](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1898161/24499680/c51788fa-1542-11e7-98fd-4e08e9c762ba.png)

3. start debug

Observe:

all but the first breakpoint are gone:
![2017-03-30_12-17-29](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1898161/24499733/e870edf0-1542-11e7-8b24-73b0f7a41b58.png)

If you turn on DAP tracing by adding `"trace":"dap"` to your launch config, you can see that the DA verifies all column breakpoints without shifting them:

```
From client: setBreakpoints({
	"source": {
		"path": "/Users/weinand/MS/Projects/TestProjects/Debugger/column.js"
	},
	"lines": [
		2,
		2,
		2,
		2,
		2
	],
	"breakpoints": [
		{
			"line": 2,
			"column": 17
		},
		{
			"line": 2,
			"column": 33
		},
		{
			"line": 2,
			"column": 49
		},
		{
			"line": 2,
			"column": 65
		},
		{
			"line": 2,
			"column": 81
		}
	],
	"sourceModified": false
})
To client: {
	"seq": 0,
	"type": "response",
	"request_seq": 3,
	"command": "setBreakpoints",
	"success": true,
	"body": {
		"breakpoints": [
			{
				"verified": true,
				"line": 2,
				"column": 17
			},
			{
				"verified": true,
				"line": 2,
				"column": 33
			},
			{
				"verified": true,
				"line": 2,
				"column": 49
			},
			{
				"verified": true,
				"line": 2,
				"column": 65
			},
			{
				"verified": true,
				"line": 2,
				"column": 81
			}
		]
	}
}
```
So there is no need to modify or delete the breakpoints.
